Since `uiputfile` doesn&#39;t create a file, you can write a simple wrapper which will check the extension of the selected file and correct it if it&#39;s different than `.app.mat` .

The wrapper can look for example like that:

    function [f,p,indx] = saveAsAppFile()
        [f,p,indx] = uiputfile({&#39;*.app.mat&#39;, &#39;App MAT files&#39;});
        f = regexprep(f, &#39;(\.app)?(\.mat)?$&#39;, &#39;\.app\.mat&#39;);
    end

It&#39;s a rather nasty workaround for the issue, but it will get the job done and it should be independent from the used operating system.


----------


If you really need the question dialog regarding overwriting already existing file and you can&#39;t wait until Mathworks solves the issue for you, you can simply extend the logic of the wrapper. E.g. you can first check which platform your user is using and if it&#39;s linux, you can manually check if the file exists. If no - you&#39;re good, if yes - pop-up your own dialog asking user if he wants to overwrite the file. In case he doesn&#39;t, just display `uiputfile` again.

And yes, of course it will slightly modify the workflow and make it less neat, but again - `uiputfile` doesn&#39;t modify the file itself so from the functionality point of view it doesn&#39;t really matter if you&#39;ll ask the user if he wants to overwrite the file when the file selection dialog is still visible or not. The effect will be exactly the same.

